1
00:00:04,604 --> 00:00:10,364
Sometimes Western people say,
“Why is there so much bowing in Asia?

2
00:00:10,364 --> 00:00:13,814
They’re bowing in Japan, they’re bowing in China,
they’re bowing in India,

3
00:00:13,845 --> 00:00:16,254
they’re touching people’s feet.
What is this?”

4
00:00:16,254 --> 00:00:19,734
[Why do we Bow?]

5
00:00:19,750 --> 00:00:33,263
They think it’s something humiliating,
less than dignified, it’s demeaning,

6
00:00:33,263 --> 00:00:35,735
 

7
00:00:35,735 --> 00:00:38,560
because their whole idea is predicated

8
00:00:38,560 --> 00:00:42,393
on this idea that everyone’s equal;

9
00:00:42,393 --> 00:00:44,640
man, woman, child,
everyone’s just equal,

10
00:00:44,640 --> 00:00:47,417
no one should be doing anything like that.

11
00:00:47,432 --> 00:00:50,088
It’s a humanistic notion.

12
00:00:50,672 --> 00:00:55,041
But what it is, at the basis of it,

13
00:00:55,041 --> 00:01:02,253
is acknowledging that 
I’m approaching a superior.

14
00:01:02,253 --> 00:01:04,878
And this is not only
an Eastern thing,

15
00:01:04,878 --> 00:01:09,794
this has been there in the West also—

16
00:01:09,794 --> 00:01:13,110
it’s still in the West,
but maybe not as much as before,

17
00:01:13,110 --> 00:01:15,984
the idea that
there’s a student and a teacher,

18
00:01:15,984 --> 00:01:21,345
and the student should be respectful 
in their approach to the teacher.

19
00:01:21,345 --> 00:01:27,258
And even the primary teacher …
when the children go to school,

20
00:01:27,258 --> 00:01:32,783
the parents tell them to treat the teacher
with great respect,

21
00:01:32,783 --> 00:01:36,590
because they know if they treat the teacher
with great respect,

22
00:01:36,590 --> 00:01:39,119
they’re going to learn.

23
00:01:39,119 --> 00:01:46,714
If they tell them, “Actually, your teacher
is just a young girl.”

24
00:01:46,714 --> 00:01:48,313
—you have some little children,

25
00:01:48,313 --> 00:01:51,204
maybe the teacher’s 18, 19, 20 years old—

26
00:01:51,204 --> 00:01:56,173
“Actually she’s just a young girl, 
she doesn’t know so much either.

27
00:01:56,173 --> 00:01:58,752
I mean, she knows what
she needs to teach you,

28
00:01:58,752 --> 00:02:01,464
but she’s deficient 
in many different ways.”

29
00:02:01,464 --> 00:02:04,548
If they give the children 
the impression that

30
00:02:04,548 --> 00:02:07,800
they don’t have to take her seriously,

31
00:02:07,800 --> 00:02:10,104
they’re not going to learn anything;

32
00:02:10,104 --> 00:02:13,235
they’re not going to benefit 
in that relationship.

33
00:02:13,235 --> 00:02:19,815
So praṇipātena means bowing, 
is the acknowledgement

34
00:02:19,815 --> 00:02:26,476
that my highest aspect, which 
we generally take physically to be the head

35
00:02:26,476 --> 00:02:29,453
—we can say the head, mind, intellect, 
heart, whatever you want to say—

36
00:02:29,453 --> 00:02:33,216
“I’m bowing the highest aspect of myself

37
00:02:33,216 --> 00:02:40,872
to the least aspect of the guru world: 
of the spiritual world.”

38
00:02:40,872 --> 00:02:43,807
So I’m taking the highest aspect of me,

39
00:02:43,807 --> 00:02:48,585
offering it, subordinating it,
to the least aspect.

40
00:02:48,585 --> 00:02:50,683
That’s the proper approach.

41
00:02:50,683 --> 00:02:56,223
So we’ll respectfully approach guru

42
00:02:56,761 --> 00:03:05,945
and inquire, ask a question,
on the basis of service necessity,

43
00:03:05,945 --> 00:03:11,361
unlike mundane knowledge
which is meant to serve you.

44
00:03:11,361 --> 00:03:15,784
Like someone goes to school,
the classic example,

45
00:03:15,784 --> 00:03:20,127
they’ll say, “Go to school, get educated,
so you can get a good job.

46
00:03:20,127 --> 00:03:24,801
Your knowledge will serve you
with financial reward.”

47
00:03:24,801 --> 00:03:29,672
Here we’re told,
“You'll become a servant of the knowledge

48
00:03:29,672 --> 00:03:36,045
that is extended to you.
It’s not to serve your lower purpose,

49
00:03:36,045 --> 00:03:40,187
but now you’re coming in connection
with a sort of knowledge

50
00:03:40,187 --> 00:03:46,177
that will require you to serve
its higher purpose.”

51
00:03:46,177 --> 00:03:50,307
So it’s different. Respectful approach
to the teacher is similar,

52
00:03:50,307 --> 00:03:53,497
but here’s knowledge not out of curiosity

53
00:03:53,497 --> 00:04:00,609
or some perceived benefit
I’ll get materially

54
00:04:00,609 --> 00:04:04,365
from acquiring this, but rather,
I’m offering myself

55
00:04:04,365 --> 00:04:07,527
in service to what is being extended to me.

56
00:04:07,527 --> 00:04:10,506
Who should you approach?

57
00:04:10,506 --> 00:04:13,370
 

58
00:04:13,370 --> 00:04:16,712
Who should you get initiated by?

59
00:04:16,812 --> 00:04:21,366
Those who are tattva-darśi.

60
00:04:21,966 --> 00:04:27,336
Some may be familiar
with the word ‘darśan’,

61
00:04:27,336 --> 00:04:32,212
it comes from the sanskrit word ‘to see’.

62
00:04:32,212 --> 00:04:35,202
People say, “Oh, darśan means
you go to see someone.”

63
00:04:35,202 --> 00:04:38,148
That’s one idea, but actually
the word darśan

64
00:04:38,148 --> 00:04:41,407
is also synonymous with philosophy,

65
00:04:41,407 --> 00:04:45,492
or a way of seeing; a viewpoint.

66
00:04:45,492 --> 00:04:48,001
So the primal guru mantra says,

67
00:04:48,001 --> 00:04:52,491
oṁ ajñāna-timirāndhasya
jñānāñjana-śalākayā

68
00:04:52,491 --> 00:04:57,078
chakṣur unmīlitaṁ yena
tasmai śrī-gurave namaḥ.

69
00:04:57,078 --> 00:05:01,472
The disciple is glorifying the guru as

70
00:05:01,472 --> 00:05:08,111
one who gifted them
with a new way of seeing.

71
00:05:08,111 --> 00:05:10,897
In fact they're saying in this śloka,

72
00:05:10,897 --> 00:05:16,183
“My eyes were covered with cataracts,

73
00:05:16,183 --> 00:05:20,517
cataracted by ignorance,
not properly estimating

74
00:05:20,517 --> 00:05:23,938
‘Who am I? What is the world
and what is my place in the world?

75
00:05:23,938 --> 00:05:28,043
What is the purpose? What is meaningful?

76
00:05:28,043 --> 00:05:30,010
What is a meaningful life?

77
00:05:30,010 --> 00:05:32,989
What is an examined life?
What is a meaningful life?

78
00:05:32,989 --> 00:05:36,384
What is the goal of life?’
All of these things.

79
00:05:36,384 --> 00:05:41,815
Not based upon short-term
perceived interest,

80
00:05:41,815 --> 00:05:45,885
preyas, but śreyas,
ultimate long term benefit.

81
00:05:45,885 --> 00:05:49,334
What is ultimately beneficial for me?”

82
00:05:49,334 --> 00:05:55,616
And that is an illusion
to our spiritual identity.

83
00:05:55,616 --> 00:06:01,707
So in that ṣloka the disciple
is praising the guru,

84
00:06:01,707 --> 00:06:08,236
saying, “My eyes were cataracted
by acquired prejudice,

85
00:06:08,236 --> 00:06:13,993
misconception, and the guru
surgically removed

86
00:06:13,993 --> 00:06:18,203
those cataracts from my eyes
so now I can see

87
00:06:18,203 --> 00:06:21,429
my spiritual identity,
my spiritual potential,

88
00:06:21,429 --> 00:06:25,387
and what is the meaning
and purpose of my life.”

